Two columns of light stretched into the night, swallowed again just past their reach. No town glow on the horizon, no headlights from behind. Around him, black trees pressed close on either side.

Mile after mile of the same flat stretch, the radio low and half-forgotten under the hum of the engine, had worn David's attention down to nothing. A bump under the tires snapped him back, and he blinked hard, sitting up straighter.

He glanced at the clock, then out at the dark pressing in on both sides. Forty-five minutes, maybe an hour — he couldn't be sure how long the same stretch of nothing had gone on.

"Wake up," he muttered.

He reached down and thumbed the dial over to AM, done with the same songs he'd been half-hearing for the last hour.

"—corn's trading at two-sixty a bushel, beans around five-eighty, winter wheat holding at three-forty on the board this morning. Suet steady. Blood meal up slightly. Human flesh down a touch on the week. Rounding out the morning report, hog futures unchanged, cotton holding firm."

The voice rolled easy into the weather without missing a beat.

"—expect clear skies through the morning hours, temperatures climbing to one-forty by early afternoon across the region, dropping to near ninety by evening."

David's hand had already started reaching for the volume knob. It stopped.

He looked at the radio. Looked back at the road. Looked at the radio again.

"What," he said, to no one.

The tone shifted, warmer, more familiar.

"—tickets are moving fast this year, organizers say, so don't wait if you want a seat for the skinning."
